article.headline: Princeton 42, Columbia 32
article.story: PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) -- Princeton football opened its defense of its Ivy League title with a 42-32, turnover-filled win over Columbia at home on Saturday. The Tigers (2-1, 1-0) survived four turnovers of their own by forcing Columbia to commit three for their fourth straight win over the Lions (1-2, 0-1). Otherwise, the top two defenses in the Ivy League had difficulty stopping each other as they combined for 965 yards of total offense. Kevin Kelleher's second interception of the day with 4:44 remaining, and the Tigers leading 35-32, dashed Columbia's chances. Princeton sealed the win with a 57-yard drive culminating in quarterback Bill Foran's second rushing touchdown of the game. Earlier, R.C. Lagomarsino scored the go-ahead touchdown on an 8-yard run 1:18 into the fourth quarter. Princeton built the lead to 35-24 less than three minutes later on Greg Mroz's 1-yard touchdown pass to Jake Staser. Columbia drove 68 yards for a touchdown from Craig Hormann to Jamal Russell on the next possession. A two-point conversion pass to Tim Paulin brought the Lions within a field goal with 7:25 left. Earlier, Princeton built a 21-3 lead on Foran's first touchdown run, a 32-yard run by Rob Toresco and 1-yard plunge by Lagomarsino.
